00:19:29,160 --> 00:19:32,038
Hey, Buzz, say hello to Rawkins!

222
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:38,869
Rawkins hears about this,
we'll both be looking for new jobs.

223
00:19:39,080 --> 00:19:40,229
Come on, sheriff!

224
00:19:49,520 --> 00:19:52,193
Well, now. What do we have here?

225
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:55,392
-lt's an angel.
-Shame on the frivolous likes of you.

226
00:19:55,600 --> 00:19:56,828
lt's an lrish angel.

227
00:19:57,040 --> 00:19:59,349
Your kith and kin pinning
their hopes on you...

228
00:19:59,560 --> 00:20:02,313
...and you go squandering your money
on a music box.

229
00:20:03,360 --> 00:20:04,793
l did it for them.

230
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,753
lt's a community guitar.

231
00:20:08,600 --> 00:20:10,955
Aye, and l'm sure that's how
you'll use it...

232
00:20:11,160 --> 00:20:13,071
...on every girl in the community.

233
00:20:13,280 --> 00:20:17,273
Daughter, that's no way to be talking
to me future business partner.

234
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:18,629
Partner?

235
00:20:18,840 --> 00:20:21,308
You accepted me money
for back taxes, didn't you?

236
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:24,159
-l intend to pay you back.
-l don't want you to.

237
00:20:24,360 --> 00:20:26,271
l just want me property rights.

238
00:20:27,400 --> 00:20:29,470
How much land you think
you're entitled to?

239
00:20:29,680 --> 00:20:33,275
An acre or so. All l really need
is a parcel of land as big as me bag...

240
00:20:33,480 --> 00:20:35,311
...on the closest point to Fort Knox.

241
00:20:35,520 --> 00:20:37,954
We are in the vicinity of Fort Knox,
are we not?

242
00:20:38,160 --> 00:20:39,388
About two miles.

243
00:20:39,600 --> 00:20:42,478
ln fact, on a warm night,
you can smell the gold.

244
00:20:44,880 --> 00:20:46,518
Have we a deal?

245
00:20:47,800 --> 00:20:49,791
-Yeah!
-Yeah!

246
00:20:51,000 --> 00:20:53,992
-lt's a deal.
-Then give me your hand, son.

247
00:20:57,120 --> 00:20:59,475
-Welcome to Rainbow Valley...
-Hi.

248
00:20:59,680 --> 00:21:02,114
...home of the most prosperous
tobacco company...

249
00:21:02,520 --> 00:21:04,909
...in this state.
And l'll wager that.

250
00:21:08,360 --> 00:21:09,918
What's your name?

251
00:21:11,200 --> 00:21:13,191
Sharon McLonergan.

252
00:21:13,400 --> 00:21:16,551
-Mine's Woody Mahoney.
-Mahoney. lt's fate.

253
00:21:17,280 --> 00:21:19,157
How'd you get so pretty...

254
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:21,357
...and so rich?

255
00:21:21,960 --> 00:21:25,953
You see, back in Glocca Morra where
we come from, there's an old legend.

256
00:21:26,160 --> 00:21:27,513
And it says:

257
00:21:27,720 --> 00:21:30,359
<i>You'll never grow old</i>
<i>And you'll never grow poor</i>

258
00:21:30,560 --> 00:21:33,677
<i>If you look to the rainbow</i>
<i>Beyond the next moor</i>

259
00:21:33,880 --> 00:21:35,711
-That's a lovely legend.
-Aye.

260
00:21:36,560 --> 00:21:39,358
-Wonder who thought it up.
-Me father.

261
00:21:39,920 --> 00:21:41,433
Finian McLonergan.

262
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:43,596
<i>On the day she was born</i>

263
00:21:43,920 --> 00:21:45,797
<i>Said her father, said he</i>

264
00:21:46,240 --> 00:21:50,028
<i>''I've an elegant legacy waiting for ye</i>

265
00:21:51,120 --> 00:21:53,475
<i>'Tis a rhyme for your lip</i>

266
00:21:54,040 --> 00:21:56,554
<i>And a song for your heart</i>

267
00:21:57,200 --> 00:22:02,399
<i>To sing it whenever</i>
<i>The world falls apart</i>

268
00:22:03,040 --> 00:22:08,319
<i>Look, look</i>
<i>Look to the rainbow</i>

269
00:22:08,560 --> 00:22:13,714
<i>Follow it over</i>
<i>The hill and stream</i>

270
00:22:14,200 --> 00:22:19,194
<i>Look, look</i>
<i>Look to the rainbow</i>

271
00:22:19,480 --> 00:22:24,679
<i>Follow the fellow</i>
<i>Who follows a dream''</i>

272
00:22:25,120 --> 00:22:30,069
<i>So I bundled me heart</i>
<i>And I roamed the world free</i>

273
00:22:30,280 --> 00:22:34,717
<i>To the East with the lark</i>
<i>To the West with the sea</i>

274
00:22:35,160 --> 00:22:40,109
<i>And I searched all the earth</i>
<i>And I scanned all the skies</i>

275
00:22:40,560 --> 00:22:46,954
<i>But I found it at last</i>
<i>In my own true love's eyes</i>

276
00:22:47,160 --> 00:22:52,280
<i>Look, look</i>
<i>Look to the rainbow</i>

277
00:22:52,600 --> 00:22:57,276
<i>Follow it over</i>
<i>The hill and stream</i>

278
00:22:58,000 --> 00:23:02,869
<i>Look, look</i>
<i>Look to the rainbow</i>

279
00:23:03,200 --> 00:23:08,718
<i>Follow the fellow</i>
<i>Who follows a dream</i>

280
00:23:09,400 --> 00:23:11,152
Follow the fellow....

281
00:23:12,360 --> 00:23:15,352
<i>Follow the fellow</i>

282
00:23:15,640 --> 00:23:18,359
<i>Follow the fellow</i>

283
00:23:18,880 --> 00:23:21,792
<i>Who follows a dream</i>

284
00:26:34,760 --> 00:26:36,318
Bye.

285
00:27:23,560 --> 00:27:25,152
Father?

286
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:28,709
Now, what would you be doing
up at this hour?

287
00:27:28,920 --> 00:27:30,069
l'm taking care of you.

288
00:27:30,280 --> 00:27:33,431
Any time the moon is full,
a McLonergan will be too.

289
00:27:33,640 --> 00:27:35,119
You go back to bed.

290
00:27:37,960 --> 00:27:40,679
Where are you going
with that bag and shovel?

291
00:27:40,880 --> 00:27:42,836
Now, will you leave me be
if l tell you?

292
00:27:43,040 --> 00:27:44,268
Aye.

293
00:27:45,520 --> 00:27:47,272
Then let me ask you this.

294
00:27:49,920 --> 00:27:53,117
What do you think makes America
different from lreland?

295
00:27:53,320 --> 00:27:54,878
Has more lrishmen.

296
00:27:56,040 --> 00:27:57,951
lt has more money.

297
00:28:01,200 --> 00:28:02,918
Everyone in America is rich.

298
00:28:03,200 --> 00:28:05,395
But, Father, are there
no poor in America?

299
00:28:05,600 --> 00:28:07,750
No ill-housed and no ill-clad?

300
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:13,159
Of course. But they're the best ill-housed
and the best ill-clad in all the world.

301
00:28:13,360 --> 00:28:15,191
Why? Why, l ask.

302
00:28:15,400 --> 00:28:17,914
And there's no man with
wit enough to tell me.

303
00:28:18,120 --> 00:28:21,157
So l'll tell you. Quote me self, quote.

304
00:28:21,360 --> 00:28:25,433
Didn't the Americans rush to dig gold
from the ground in California in 1849?

305
00:28:25,640 --> 00:28:26,789
So l've heard.

306
00:28:27,000 --> 00:28:29,878
And didn't they plant it in the soil
at Fort Knox later?

307
00:28:30,080 --> 00:28:31,513
-Granted.
-Well, that's it!

308
00:28:32,200 --> 00:28:36,478
You see, there's something about
the soil in and around Fort Knox...

309
00:28:36,680 --> 00:28:39,114
...that gives a magical quality to gold.

310
00:28:39,320 --> 00:28:42,153
-Father--
-The gold radiates a powerful influence...

311
00:28:42,360 --> 00:28:45,591
...throughout America.
lt activates assembly lines in Detroit...

312
00:28:45,800 --> 00:28:48,951
...it makes skyscrapers sprout
from the gutters of New York...

313
00:28:49,160 --> 00:28:53,039
...and it produces a bumper crop
of millionaires. And that...

314
00:28:55,280 --> 00:28:57,669
...is the McLonergan theory
of economics.

315
00:28:58,240 --> 00:28:59,992
And that's why we came
to America?

316
00:29:00,200 --> 00:29:03,192
Aye. To bury me pot of gold.

317
00:29:03,400 --> 00:29:05,789
Now, you go back to bed.
lt's a witching night.

318
00:29:24,360 --> 00:29:27,352
Aye. Very scary place.

319
00:31:03,680 --> 00:31:06,478
l'll.... l'll.... l'll....

320
00:31:32,200 --> 00:31:33,428
One, two...

321
00:31:33,640 --> 00:31:36,677
...four, five, six, seven, eight.

322
00:31:48,080 --> 00:31:50,833
<i>Green is the color of the shamrock</i>

323
00:31:51,640 --> 00:31:53,676
<i>And the grass on Blarney Hill</i>

324
00:31:54,320 --> 00:31:57,232
<i>Oh, the darlin' green of Ireland</i>

325
00:31:57,640 --> 00:31:59,995
<i>And the good old dollar bill</i>

326
00:33:33,280 --> 00:33:34,918
God be with you.

327
00:33:37,520 --> 00:33:39,875
God and Mary be with ye?

328
00:33:41,200 --> 00:33:43,714
God, Mary and St. Patrick be with ye.

329
00:33:43,920 --> 00:33:47,117
God, Mary, St. Patrick
and St. Ozymandias be with ye.

330
00:33:47,320 --> 00:33:50,232
-Ozymandias? l never heard of him.
-He was a special saint.

331
00:33:50,480 --> 00:33:53,711
He's the patron saint of
all the leprechauns of Glocca Morra.

332
00:33:54,840 --> 00:33:56,831
-My name is Og.
-Og from Glocca Morra?

333
00:33:57,040 --> 00:33:58,792
-Me native heath.
-Right.

334
00:33:59,200 --> 00:34:02,317
You're an imposter. You can't be
a leprechaun, you're too tall!

335
00:34:02,520 --> 00:34:05,193
l know, and l'm getting taller!

336
00:34:05,440 --> 00:34:07,829
l need your help, Mr. McLonergan.

337
00:34:08,280 --> 00:34:10,510
-Me help?
-Aye.

338
00:34:10,720 --> 00:34:12,836
That calls for a toast.

339
00:34:13,200 --> 00:34:16,510
l rise to welcome you to America.

340
00:34:17,240 --> 00:34:20,550
-How are things in Glocca Morra?
-Alas, alack and willy-wally.

341
00:34:20,760 --> 00:34:22,910
l weep for Glocca Morra
and all lreland.

342
00:34:23,120 --> 00:34:24,917
You weep? Why, what's happened?

343
00:34:25,440 --> 00:34:27,635
A blight has fallen over lreland.

344
00:34:27,840 --> 00:34:31,150
-The British are back.
-Never seen such a curse befall a folk...

345
00:34:31,360 --> 00:34:35,638
...in all me 459 years.

346
00:34:37,480 --> 00:34:39,630
Alas, poor lreland.

347
00:34:39,920 --> 00:34:41,990
-Poor lreland.
-Poor lreland!

348
00:34:42,200 --> 00:34:44,191
-Suffering lreland.
-Suffering lreland!

349
00:34:47,640 --> 00:34:51,349
-The native land!
-Oh, me native land!

350
00:34:56,600 --> 00:34:59,637
A fine lot of fairyfolk you are,
letting all this happen.

351
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:01,876
Why don't you wish it away.

352
00:35:02,720 --> 00:35:04,517
We lost the power.

353
00:35:04,720 --> 00:35:07,871
You mean you've gone and lost
the power to make wishes?

354
00:35:08,080 --> 00:35:10,275
-Aye.
-What has lreland to live for now?

355
00:35:10,480 --> 00:35:12,835
-Answer me that.
-Doom and gloom!

356
00:35:13,080 --> 00:35:16,868
Doom and gloom!

357
00:35:17,120 --> 00:35:19,759
-Who's the author of this foul outrage?
-A monster.

358
00:35:19,960 --> 00:35:21,279
-A monster?
-Aye.

359
00:35:21,480 --> 00:35:24,677
You mean the old flame-breathing type,
with the head of a dragon?

360
00:35:24,880 --> 00:35:28,873
Oh, no. This is a tiny, wee monster.
He's about...

361
00:35:29,080 --> 00:35:30,911
-...your size.
-Who is he?

362
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:32,439
Who is this monster?

363
00:35:32,640 --> 00:35:35,871
Excuse me for pointing,
Mr. McLonergan, but it's you.

364
00:35:36,200 --> 00:35:38,589
-Me?
-You brought the blight on yourself...

365
00:35:38,800 --> 00:35:41,189
...when you stole our crock of gold!

366
00:35:41,440 --> 00:35:44,113
The little crock that gives us
all the power to wish.

367
00:35:44,360 --> 00:35:46,237
Don't be superstitious, it's bad luck!

368
00:35:46,440 --> 00:35:49,477
-Give it back, Mr. McLonergan.
-How do you know l've got it?

369
00:35:49,680 --> 00:35:52,797
Me magnetic feathers pointed you out
all the way from lreland.

370
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,753
Feathers, who's the culprit?

371
00:35:56,160 --> 00:35:58,276
Oh, me arthritis!

372
00:35:59,160 --> 00:36:02,436
Give it back, Mr. McLonergan,
before a great evil befalls you.

373
00:36:02,640 --> 00:36:05,154
Can't you postpone your wishing
a couple of months?

374
00:36:05,360 --> 00:36:08,557
Gold was never meant for mankind.

375
00:36:08,760 --> 00:36:12,833
lt's a fairyland metal
that only fairyfolk can use.

376
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:17,552
ln the hands of a mortal,
it can only bring...

377
00:36:18,480 --> 00:36:20,357
...doom and gloom.

378
00:36:20,560 --> 00:36:23,028
Doom and gloom!

379
00:36:23,240 --> 00:36:25,470
Doom and gloom.
Stop your wailing, leprechaun.

380
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:28,035
l've come to a decision.
l deny your existence.

381
00:36:28,240 --> 00:36:30,435
-You're a figment of me imagination.
-l am?

382
00:36:30,680 --> 00:36:33,478
To prove it, l'm going to walk
through you.

383
00:36:34,240 --> 00:36:37,312
Step aside. There, what did l tell you?

384
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:39,596
This is dreadful.

385
00:36:39,960 --> 00:36:41,473
-l don't exist.
-Of course not.

386
00:36:41,680 --> 00:36:43,955
l'm always seeing things.
Ask me daughter.

387
00:36:44,880 --> 00:36:48,236
But if l don't exist, how is it
l'm gradually becoming mortal?

388
00:36:48,560 --> 00:36:50,437
-The saints preserve us. You are.
-Aye.

389
00:36:50,640 --> 00:36:54,679
So are all the other little leprechauns
ever since you stole our crock of gold.

390
00:36:54,880 --> 00:36:59,158
Look at me. Look!
lt's crept past me ankles already.

391
00:36:59,360 --> 00:37:02,158
-Can't you hold out until the winter?
-l don't know.

392
00:37:02,360 --> 00:37:05,113
l got a peculiar human feeling
in me thighs lately.

393
00:37:05,320 --> 00:37:07,754
Your thighs? Don't let it
go any higher, man.

394
00:37:09,960 --> 00:37:12,872
-Mary and Joseph, lreland's ruined.
-Father!

395
00:37:13,080 --> 00:37:14,559
-Someone's coming.
-Me daughter.

396
00:37:14,880 --> 00:37:19,317
And now that you're half mortal,
you're indecent. Here, here, take these.

397
00:37:20,800 --> 00:37:22,756
Now, you heard me, now.

398
00:37:23,000 --> 00:37:26,709
You take those clothes and--

399
00:37:26,960 --> 00:37:29,633
Father!

400
00:37:29,840 --> 00:37:31,910
Father!

401
00:37:33,200 --> 00:37:34,679
Sharon!

402
00:37:36,080 --> 00:37:38,674
Mr. McLonergan!

403
00:37:38,880 --> 00:37:42,634
-Father!
-Sharon!

404
00:37:43,760 --> 00:37:47,116
-Father!
-Sharon!

405
00:37:47,920 --> 00:37:51,549
Mr. McLonergan!

406
00:37:51,760 --> 00:37:54,718
-Father!
-What fools these mortals be.

407
00:37:56,280 --> 00:37:58,589
-Mr.--
-Father--

408
00:38:00,160 --> 00:38:02,151
Father!

409
00:38:07,080 --> 00:38:10,117
Now, what's a nice girl like you
doing in a place like this?

410
00:38:10,320 --> 00:38:12,197
Oh, it's you, Mr. Mahoney.

411
00:38:12,400 --> 00:38:15,073
l was looking for me father.

412
00:38:15,800 --> 00:38:17,791
Not too long ago...

413
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:21,117
...they find a girl in the forest
in the middle of the night...

414
00:38:21,320 --> 00:38:22,878
...they'd think that she was...

415
00:38:23,760 --> 00:38:25,159
...a witch.

416
00:38:25,520 --> 00:38:27,317
ls that so? Well....

417
00:38:27,520 --> 00:38:30,557
lf you'll excuse me, l--
l'll be saying good evening to you.

418
00:38:31,120 --> 00:38:33,190
You're not afraid of the werewolves?

419
00:38:33,680 --> 00:38:35,398
Werewolves?

420
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:39,552
Our valley has its legends too,
you know.

421
00:38:41,600 --> 00:38:44,990
Haven't you noticed how strange
the sky looks?

422
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:48,195
lt is a trifle strange.

423
00:38:49,360 --> 00:38:51,191
And look at the moon.

424
00:38:52,880 --> 00:38:54,871
lt is a cold, full moon.

425
00:38:55,080 --> 00:38:57,071
The legend of the valley:

426
00:38:57,600 --> 00:38:59,875
When the sky is strange...

427
00:39:00,080 --> 00:39:02,036
...and the moon is full...

428
00:39:02,800 --> 00:39:05,234
...the werewolves prowl.

429
00:39:05,680 --> 00:39:08,035
-Unless....
-Unless?

430
00:39:08,520 --> 00:39:11,353
That's a complicated part,
and l know you're in a hurry.

431
00:39:11,560 --> 00:39:15,269
Oh, no, Mr. Mahoney. l'd like to know
the complicated part of the legend.

432
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:17,994
lt's how to make yourself immune
from the werewolf.

433
00:39:18,200 --> 00:39:20,077
Well, how would l be doing that?

434
00:39:22,040 --> 00:39:23,439
Well...

435
00:39:23,920 --> 00:39:29,199
...you have to stand very, very close
to the nicest, handsomest fellow around.

436
00:39:36,280 --> 00:39:38,077
That must be you.

437
00:39:40,080 --> 00:39:41,479
Must be.

438
00:39:44,480 --> 00:39:47,392
Then you make yourself comfortable
on the grass.

439
00:39:52,680 --> 00:39:55,319
Now, you blink your eyes twice...

440
00:39:56,600 --> 00:39:58,318
...and keep them closed.

441
00:40:00,680 --> 00:40:02,352
Now you say...

442
00:40:03,160 --> 00:40:07,312
...''petrified parsley'' over and over,
real fast.

443
00:40:07,560 --> 00:40:12,395
Petrified parsley, petrified parsley,
petrified parsley....

444
00:40:12,600 --> 00:40:13,953
-Feel immune yet?
-No.

445
00:40:14,160 --> 00:40:17,789
Petrified parsley, petrified parsley,
petrified parsley....

446
00:40:36,760 --> 00:40:38,751
That's a lovely legend.

447
00:40:39,720 --> 00:40:41,392
Who made it up?

448
00:40:42,120 --> 00:40:43,075
l did.

449
00:40:47,800 --> 00:40:55,115
<i>I look at you and suddenly</i>

450
00:40:55,720 --> 00:40:59,429
<i>Something in your eyes I see</i>

451
00:40:59,760 --> 00:41:05,710
<i>Soon begins bewitching me</i>

452
00:41:05,920 --> 00:41:10,471
<i>It's that old devil moon</i>

453
00:41:10,920 --> 00:41:15,198
<i>That you stole from the skies</i>

454
00:41:15,680 --> 00:41:20,356
<i>It's that old devil moon</i>

455
00:41:20,560 --> 00:41:23,916
<i>In your eyes</i>

456
00:41:25,200 --> 00:41:29,955
<i>You and your glance</i>
<i>Make this romance</i>

457
00:41:31,280 --> 00:41:34,238
<i>Too hot to handle</i>

458
00:41:34,960 --> 00:41:39,272
<i>Stars in the night</i>
<i>Blazing their light</i>

459
00:41:39,640 --> 00:41:45,590
